            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_217wh' title='Col. 217WH &mdash; HC Deb 09 January 2002 vol 377 c217WH' name='column_217wh' href='#column_217wh' rel='bookmark'>217WH</a>
            I want to discuss the railway infrastructure in Wales, particularly mid-Wales, in the light of recent events such as Hatfield and the Government's takeover of Railtrack in October. The Cambrian line in mid-Wales is one of the most rural lines in the United Kingdom. Although there might be some hesitation, I could name every rural railway station on it without fear of repetition&#x2014;aficionados of the panel game "Just a Minute" would recognise the style of Clement Freud&#x2014;for more than one minute and still not reach Machynlleth. I want to impress on hon. Members that the Cambrian line is a rural line that is absolutely vital to mid-Wales.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
